1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:27,016
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:27,435 --> 00:00:32,325
homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:35,350 --> 00:00:39,939
So, we've come to the end of our three-week retreat.

4
00:00:40,140 --> 00:00:41,884
Some of you have been here for three weeks.

5
00:00:43,012 --> 00:00:49,140
Some joined a couple of weeks back and one or two of you came this week.

6
00:00:50,042 --> 00:01:01,999
So as usual at the end of a retreat, there's this translation, you might say, of what we've come to understand in our practice into our daily life.

7
00:01:03,127 --> 00:01:10,179
And one of the things the Buddha did was he left, I want to start with the monastic order so you have some idea.

8
00:01:10,558 --> 00:01:13,844
He said that he had left the Dharma and the Vinaya.

9
00:01:14,426 --> 00:01:19,194
He didn't just leave the Dharma, which would be the teaching, the practice of meditation and all that.

10
00:01:19,233 --> 00:01:21,137
He also left the Vinaya.

11
00:01:21,156 --> 00:01:23,060
The Vinaya is the rule of the monks.

12
00:01:23,820 --> 00:01:27,867
And he considered that of equal importance, the Dharma and the Vinaya.

13
00:01:27,847 --> 00:01:42,751
And he obviously saw that the institution that had developed around him was of importance as maybe not so much...

14
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:45,602
to maintain the teaching.

15
00:01:45,924 --> 00:01:49,868
I'm sure that was on his mind, but as exemplars.

16
00:01:50,530 --> 00:02:07,394
So as the order grew, especially after the first 20 years, when it seems people joined who were not of the same caliber as the first intake, these rules began to appear, all sorts of rules.

17
00:02:07,733 --> 00:02:12,621
So there were serious ones for which you lose the robe,

18
00:02:13,106 --> 00:02:24,941
such as stealing, any, if you excuse, any sexual penetration to the depth of a mustard seed.

19
00:02:28,044 --> 00:02:30,927
Very precise, very precise.

20
00:02:30,948 --> 00:02:32,389
In any aperture, by the way.

21
00:02:33,070 --> 00:02:38,456
So you can see he's got it really taped, you know, there's no way out of it.

22
00:02:39,955 --> 00:02:51,108
And then there's all sorts of rules about behavior between monks and especially women and for nuns with men.

23
00:02:51,127 --> 00:03:02,721
And there's what you might call institutional rules, which define the institution and those rules which are really to do with morality.

24
00:03:02,901 --> 00:03:05,944
And they're all mixed together, which is rather interesting.

25
00:03:06,025 --> 00:03:08,527
It's actually a very...

26
00:03:10,735 --> 00:03:28,389
illogical code it's really to do with the punishments or that's not quite the right word in buddhism the consequences of what happens if you break these rules so the rules come in in the measure of their

27
00:03:28,370 --> 00:03:29,411
of their consequence.

28
00:03:29,431 --> 00:03:31,875
So the ones I've just mentioned, you lose your robe.

29
00:03:32,235 --> 00:03:34,057
There's no ceremony for leaving.

30
00:03:34,177 --> 00:03:37,763
You don't have to go and make this great confession in front of thousands of people.

31
00:03:38,324 --> 00:03:41,609
You just disrobe, you just disappear.

32
00:03:43,512 --> 00:03:51,302
That's if you can handle the shame and the horror of being a monk, having broken these rules, of course, you carry on being a monk.

33
00:03:52,123 --> 00:03:53,466
But that would be very hard, I think.

34
00:03:54,948 --> 00:04:00,919
But there's others which demand a meeting that you have to tell what you've done.

35
00:04:01,542 --> 00:04:06,491
Like, for instance, an obvious one, touching a woman in a lustful way.

36
00:04:06,992 --> 00:04:10,741
You have to confess to five and you have to be separated for at least six nights.

37
00:04:11,641 --> 00:04:16,331
And then you have to get 20 monks to get you back into the order to reestablish you.

38
00:04:16,750 --> 00:04:17,932
unless you're out in the cold.

39
00:04:19,634 --> 00:04:23,699
There's others where you have something which you shouldn't have and you have to give it up.

40
00:04:25,362 --> 00:04:27,024
So, you know, I don't know.

41
00:04:30,009 --> 00:04:33,915
For instance, sometimes monks will buy something

42
00:04:33,894 --> 00:04:36,838
But it'll be like, say, the scriptures.

43
00:04:36,879 --> 00:04:41,865
But because they bought it with money, it's not to be had.

44
00:04:41,906 --> 00:04:43,848
So often you have to give that up.

45
00:04:44,350 --> 00:04:46,773
But often that's given back to the person, you see.

46
00:04:46,793 --> 00:04:50,257
It's just like a reminder, really, that they shouldn't be doing that.

47
00:04:51,019 --> 00:04:52,661
Then there's all sorts of little rules.

48
00:04:53,122 --> 00:04:57,449
And then we get down to, and I'll just show you how nitty gritty it is.

49
00:04:57,468 --> 00:04:58,350
And I don't know...

50
00:04:59,326 --> 00:05:03,692
And the Buddha said to Ananda, look, these lesser rules, you can get rid of them, you see.

51
00:05:04,093 --> 00:05:08,038
Well, of course, Ananda didn't ask what he actually meant by these little rules.

52
00:05:08,079 --> 00:05:09,841
So he was heavily blamed at the council.

53
00:05:10,783 --> 00:05:16,651
So nobody's ever had the gumption to say, well, look, you know, we can get rid of this rule.

54
00:05:16,672 --> 00:05:17,994
But he gets down to this, you see.

55
00:05:18,033 --> 00:05:29,129
And just note the difference, even though they're all just put in any old order, not making a distinction between what is moral and what is institutional.

56
00:05:30,055 --> 00:05:36,144
So you get one which is, for instance, I shall not look enviously at another's bowl.

57
00:05:36,163 --> 00:05:43,675
So when you're sitting there at table, have you sort of peeked over and thought, look at that, how could he take so much?

58
00:05:43,694 --> 00:05:51,747
So it's looking, the envy of looking at somebody's food, you see.

59
00:05:52,307 --> 00:05:55,733
But then you've got things like what you might call just etiquette.

60
00:05:55,752 --> 00:05:58,797
I shall not eat stuffing out the cheeks like a monkey.

61
00:06:00,531 --> 00:06:04,255
You see, I shall not make a chapu chapu sound.

62
00:06:05,576 --> 00:06:10,843
And I shall not eat making a suru suru sound.

63
00:06:11,204 --> 00:06:21,954
So there's all these bands of rules about behaviour, you know, which all really have to do with a certain etiquette.

64
00:06:22,156 --> 00:06:25,798
And I suppose you've got to ask yourself, why?

65
00:06:26,079 --> 00:06:28,141
You know, why such a...

66
00:06:28,865 --> 00:06:32,550
why such a finickity-ness about things, you see?

67
00:06:32,571 --> 00:06:41,024
So the only way you can explain that is the way the Buddha talked about himself.

68
00:06:41,064 --> 00:06:45,170
He said, who sees the Buddha sees the Dharma, and who sees the Dharma sees the Buddha.

69
00:06:45,752 --> 00:06:50,819
So in other words, your behavior is a manifestation of your wisdom.

70
00:06:51,901 --> 00:06:56,187
And there's something about somebody who is

71
00:06:57,603 --> 00:07:09,101
awakened or liberated, whatever, however you wish to name it, that there's a certain dignity about the person, a certain way of behaving which suggests a refinement.

72
00:07:10,084 --> 00:07:13,249
So this whole business of ethics, and we'll

73
00:07:14,072 --> 00:07:26,391
we'll talk about why it's so important, is moving from the gross, you know, like finally we've come to the end of killing people, thieving from the next door neighbour, you know, and swearing at them.

74
00:07:26,791 --> 00:07:29,274
And we've sort of come away from all that.

75
00:07:29,815 --> 00:07:37,127
But there's a whole section of behaviour which is a refinement to do with the beautiful mind.

76
00:07:38,490 --> 00:07:45,538
So we're moving towards beautifying the mind and this naturally expresses itself in the way we behave.

77
00:07:47,401 --> 00:07:57,692
Now, to go back a step and wonder why ethics is so important, remember the sequence of events in daily life.

78
00:07:58,312 --> 00:08:02,338
There is always this underground ignorance, right?

79
00:08:02,317 --> 00:08:04,581
Now, remember, that's the wrong word, really.

80
00:08:04,641 --> 00:08:05,882
We should say not knowing.

81
00:08:06,103 --> 00:08:10,848
In fact, I did find the right word, nescience, but nobody knows it.

82
00:08:11,350 --> 00:08:13,271
So I thought, there's no point in using it.

83
00:08:14,293 --> 00:08:22,343
Every time I say, translate avidya, I've always got to do this sort of double take on it and say, well, it's not culpable ignorance.

84
00:08:22,363 --> 00:08:23,826
It's just, you don't know.

85
00:08:23,886 --> 00:08:26,610
And then there's the mistake we make.

86
00:08:26,790 --> 00:08:28,572
What is the mistake we make?

87
00:08:29,314 --> 00:08:31,937
The mistake is to think we're human beings.

88
00:08:33,621 --> 00:08:40,158
See, once you realize that, that is a conventional reality, right?

89
00:08:40,177 --> 00:08:41,501
I mean, we're not apes, right?

90
00:08:41,701 --> 00:08:44,690
But in an ultimate reality, we're not human beings.

91
00:08:44,710 --> 00:08:46,293
We're not this body, heart, mind.

92
00:08:47,155 --> 00:08:49,621
That's what I mean when I say human being.

93
00:08:50,513 --> 00:09:05,361
So having made the mistake of wanting to be this, believing ourselves to be this human being, what is it that we really, really deep down in our, in the most deepest recesses of our, what do we want?

94
00:09:05,402 --> 00:09:10,010
To be happy, isn't it?

95
00:09:10,030 --> 00:09:11,273
You just want to be happy.

96
00:09:12,518 --> 00:09:14,539
And you can define that in any way you want.

97
00:09:14,600 --> 00:09:15,660
For some people, it's money.

98
00:09:15,701 --> 00:09:16,663
For some people, it's love.

99
00:09:17,023 --> 00:09:20,187
But basically, we're all searching for this happiness.

100
00:09:21,567 --> 00:09:25,753
Now, our mistake, of course, is to seek happiness in the sensual world.

101
00:09:26,413 --> 00:09:35,943
And that leads us into three relationships which are undermining our sensuality.

102
00:09:36,700 --> 00:09:41,726
even though sometimes it doesn't seem like that or feel like that.

103
00:09:41,746 --> 00:09:46,715
So the first one is, of course, that you generally feel more happy the more you have.

104
00:09:47,556 --> 00:09:50,580
And more is a noun, just more.

105
00:09:51,902 --> 00:09:56,830
So more friends, more money, better job.

106
00:09:57,149 --> 00:09:59,052
And it just goes more, more, more.

107
00:09:59,594 --> 00:10:04,581
And what we don't realize is that the more you have, the more vulnerable you are.

108
00:10:05,505 --> 00:10:08,477
Because the more you have, the more you have to lose.

109
00:10:09,421 --> 00:10:14,200
And the more you have to lose puts you into a state of fear, a state of anxiety.

110
00:10:15,277 --> 00:10:24,451
And this anxiety, of course, is underlying all our pleasures in life, because we know that it could all disappear in a trice.

111
00:10:25,033 --> 00:10:32,625
In fact, the news is now that the world is going to dip again into a huge recession, it seems.

112
00:10:33,145 --> 00:10:35,369
So a lot of people are going to lose work.

113
00:10:35,428 --> 00:10:37,673
There's going to be misery out there, is it?

114
00:10:39,390 --> 00:10:43,437
Hopefully it doesn't affect you, of course.

115
00:10:44,337 --> 00:10:59,961
So and on top of that, of course, there's this aversion, there's this defense mechanism where anybody that is undermining your possessions is to be seen as an enemy and must be must be annihilated at all costs.

116
00:11:01,123 --> 00:11:05,769
So you can see that these three these three

117
00:11:06,778 --> 00:11:29,378
dispositions relate to show us our relationship to the world we're either acquiring something or we are defending something or we're running away from something hiding from something so from these three dispositions all our negative all our unwholesome actions arise and

118
00:11:29,880 --> 00:11:40,072
you know, the greed, all the hatred and the spite and the revenge and all the other side too, the anxiety and the depression.

119
00:11:41,953 --> 00:11:44,836
It's difficult to define depression these days.

120
00:11:44,856 --> 00:11:47,500
People seem to have various definitions.

121
00:11:47,519 --> 00:11:53,846
But when I personally talk about depression, I just mean those feelings that you have

122
00:11:53,826 --> 00:12:21,623
when you get in contact with something in your in your in your makeup which um is trying to come up but you don't let it out so you're having a clue what it is it could be suppressed grief it could be suppressed fear whatever it is but as it comes up as it tries to surface there's an unwillingness to go there and there's a fear of it because you just don't know what's uh what's

123
00:12:21,602 --> 00:12:41,231
you know what turbulence that is in the heart i mean that's one of our big problems in meditation is to is to get that um to to be able to to go into the into the bonfires and and to feel comfortable there you know not to be not to feel you know burn up with them so

124
00:12:41,582 --> 00:12:48,234
These three dispositions lead us then into these negative actions.

125
00:12:48,835 --> 00:12:54,524
And because of that, we have the consequences that come of it.

126
00:12:55,186 --> 00:12:57,570
Technically, it's called vipaka, karma.

127
00:12:57,590 --> 00:12:59,693
Karma is the act, vipaka is the product.

128
00:12:59,754 --> 00:13:05,604
But these days, of course, it's become in our language to talk about your karma.

129
00:13:05,624 --> 00:13:07,606
Anything that happens to you is your karma.

130
00:13:09,780 --> 00:13:16,374
Just on an aside there, we need to be clear about what personal karma is.

131
00:13:16,433 --> 00:13:31,384
Your personal, by which I mean that karma which is preventing us from achieving liberation, are these dispositions within us, which every time we act upon them get worse.

132
00:13:32,038 --> 00:13:33,860
That's our personal karma.

133
00:13:34,162 --> 00:13:38,488
What happens to us from the outside could be caused by a myriad reasons.

134
00:13:38,567 --> 00:13:39,990
The Buddha is quite clear about that.

135
00:13:40,711 --> 00:13:49,302
Just because you catch a cold doesn't mean that's because you pushed somebody out in the snow many years ago.

136
00:13:50,524 --> 00:13:53,827
It just means somebody sneezed at you and you got mad.

137
00:13:54,802 --> 00:14:05,779
So, I mean, it's not it's not that's not your personal karma, how you deal with it and how you how you feel about the person who sneezed in your face is your personal karma.

138
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:08,403
That's what your personal karma is.

139
00:14:08,423 --> 00:14:14,754
So, OK, so here we have this idea that we started off with this wrong understanding.

140
00:14:14,813 --> 00:14:18,600
We've created this mayhem and now we have to go back on it.

141
00:14:18,884 --> 00:14:26,474
And our first attempt through the meditation is to let the heart manifest all its turbulences.

142
00:14:26,894 --> 00:14:35,046
And we find that just by allowing it to do that, these turbulences just die away.

143
00:14:35,927 --> 00:14:38,630
They begin to evaporate, you might say.

144
00:14:40,028 --> 00:14:42,071
And that, of course, is not a short process.

145
00:14:42,130 --> 00:14:46,697
That's going to be, I mean, restlessness doesn't go to the very end.

146
00:14:47,437 --> 00:14:52,565
Not until that moment when we are fully liberated does restlessness leave us.

147
00:14:53,225 --> 00:14:56,711
And it depends how you want to define restlessness.

148
00:14:56,730 --> 00:15:08,246
The way I see it is that it's all these defilements, but now at such a low level that it's experienced by the person as a sort of discomfort, discomfort.

149
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:16,503
And of course, conceit, which is at the base of this relationship, the I am, I am me, doesn't go either.

150
00:15:16,903 --> 00:15:21,192
So it's not as though we're ever going to be able to say, well, that's done.

151
00:15:21,212 --> 00:15:30,251
You know, I'm finished with worrying about my dark side, you know, because it's always going to be there in some little way to the very end.

152
00:15:30,703 --> 00:15:35,510
Now, our passage now is, first of all, to undermine that.

153
00:15:35,530 --> 00:15:38,014
But then, of course, it's to develop the good heart.

154
00:15:38,034 --> 00:15:42,159
It's to develop ourselves as beautiful people.

155
00:15:42,179 --> 00:15:47,768
And the reason for that is because this is a manifestation of the Buddha within.

156
00:15:48,349 --> 00:15:52,014
This is what we mean by the Dharma, by wisdom, by wisdom in action.

157
00:15:52,495 --> 00:15:55,799
We mean, how does it manifest in the person?

158
00:15:57,181 --> 00:16:03,129
And it manifests, of course, in all the virtues, and we can go through the perfections, as they're known.

159
00:16:04,231 --> 00:16:08,818
But it also manifests in this sort of refinement of behavior.

160
00:16:09,340 --> 00:16:10,861
You know, refinement of behavior.

161
00:16:13,466 --> 00:16:19,355
And that's why there are all these little finickety rules in the monastic orders.

162
00:16:21,118 --> 00:16:23,761
Now, on another tack...

163
00:16:25,480 --> 00:16:29,975
We have to question what this more is, you see.

164
00:16:30,817 --> 00:16:36,216
And here's the Buddha telling us what we actually need.

165
00:16:36,836 --> 00:16:39,298
in order to live the spiritual life.

166
00:16:39,318 --> 00:16:44,583
So don't confuse this with what we need in order to live the social life.

167
00:16:45,264 --> 00:16:48,388
You know, like you need money for a bus, you need et cetera, et cetera.

168
00:16:48,748 --> 00:16:55,494
But right at the base of our needs in order to live the spiritual life, we have these four requisites.

169
00:16:56,134 --> 00:16:59,037
So I'll read them out as they come.

170
00:16:59,057 --> 00:17:06,304
So wisely reflecting, I use the robe, so clothes, to ward off the cold, ward off the heat,

171
00:17:06,284 --> 00:17:14,021
ward off the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, burning and creeping things, and only for the sake of modesty.

172
00:17:14,603 --> 00:17:21,880
So there's no mention here of, you know, fashion shows.

173
00:17:21,859 --> 00:17:25,405
I mean, you know, like what is the monk about town wearing at this moment?

174
00:17:26,748 --> 00:17:29,531
You know, it's like it doesn't it doesn't come into the definition.

175
00:17:29,571 --> 00:17:31,454
It's just straightforward.

176
00:17:31,474 --> 00:17:33,979
You're wearing clothes to protect yourself.

177
00:17:33,999 --> 00:17:40,189
Unfortunately, we've lost that connection with nature, which allows us to go around naked.

178
00:17:40,169 --> 00:17:44,954
You know, like every other animal that we see here, they found ways of bearing with nature.

179
00:17:44,994 --> 00:17:46,277
They can live in nature.

180
00:17:47,397 --> 00:17:52,825
When we had that minus 21 up here during that very cold winter, we never had minus 21.

181
00:17:53,506 --> 00:18:00,894
There were horses out in the field just standing like like statues close to each other, not against each other.

182
00:18:03,305 --> 00:18:32,586
they bear I mean at night all day long and there was hardly any fodder though the farmer was bringing bales of fodder during the day but day after day I can't remember how long it lasted but it was a long time wasn't it at least a month wasn't it I remember that terrible winter and they didn't die they just stood in the cold and of course we have to well we need hot water bottles

183
00:18:34,287 --> 00:18:40,594
So you can see there's a certain disconnect being a human being with nature.

184
00:18:41,035 --> 00:18:43,636
But you can see here, that's all you actually need.

185
00:18:43,998 --> 00:18:49,243
You only need the clothes to protect yourself from nature.

186
00:18:50,345 --> 00:18:51,625
However, that might manifest.

187
00:18:53,067 --> 00:18:54,769
You know, in the East, it's mosquitoes and stuff.

188
00:18:56,571 --> 00:19:00,636
When it comes to alms food, you see, I use the alms food not for fun.

189
00:19:01,657 --> 00:19:03,720
That kills it immediately, doesn't it?

190
00:19:04,409 --> 00:19:33,386
not for pleasure uh this is indulgence i mean it's in a sense that's a wrong translation not not for fattening and not for beautification see but only for the maintenance and nourishment of the body for keeping it healthy for helping with the holy life thinking thus and this is what we say in a slightly different way at our meal times i will allay hunger without overeating so that i may continue to live blamelessly and at ease

191
00:19:33,873 --> 00:19:42,484
So when you're taking food, you see, get down to that, you know, remind yourself of what you actually need, you see.

192
00:19:42,885 --> 00:19:46,171
So it doesn't need to be really, really tasty.

193
00:19:46,191 --> 00:19:48,173
It doesn't need to be particularly varied.

194
00:19:48,554 --> 00:19:54,803
I mean, here, I think we go through every vegetable that is on earth by the end of the week.

195
00:19:56,105 --> 00:20:00,131
And so many types of beans and so many types of pulses.

196
00:20:00,852 --> 00:20:03,576
And I often think, well, I'm not so sure

197
00:20:03,556 --> 00:20:10,547
That's particularly good for us because the body has to work at thinking, hold on, this is cauliflower.

198
00:20:11,048 --> 00:20:15,575
This is broad beans, what am I going to do?

199
00:20:15,914 --> 00:20:24,448
So the body has to keep manufacturing different enzymes to compete with the amount of food, all these different foods.

200
00:20:24,468 --> 00:20:29,496
Whereas in the old days, it was just a chop and two veg.

201
00:20:29,594 --> 00:20:30,134
And that was it.

202
00:20:30,154 --> 00:20:31,396
And you had that every week.

203
00:20:32,058 --> 00:20:34,222
You had fish with boiled potatoes, and that was it.

204
00:20:34,423 --> 00:20:35,064
I remember that.

205
00:20:37,868 --> 00:20:40,413
And all these drinks, millions of drinks.

206
00:20:40,453 --> 00:20:43,660
Well, in the old days, it was just tea, wasn't it?

207
00:20:43,680 --> 00:20:44,321
You want some tea?

208
00:20:44,342 --> 00:20:45,042
You're not bothering.

209
00:20:45,683 --> 00:20:49,009
That was the welcome, wasn't it?

210
00:20:49,029 --> 00:20:50,953
Do you want a cup of tea?

211
00:20:50,973 --> 00:20:51,634
You're not bothering.

212
00:20:52,396 --> 00:20:53,137
I'd say, yeah, all right.

213
00:20:54,316 --> 00:21:04,273
So it's good to remind ourselves about, you know, this refinement, about getting back to the basics of what we actually need.

214
00:21:06,136 --> 00:21:09,844
And then we come to reflecting our lodgings where we live, you see.

215
00:21:10,384 --> 00:21:14,231
So again, the Buddha is only concerned with warding off the cold.

216
00:21:14,396 --> 00:21:43,948
ward off heat ward off the touch of flies mosquitoes wind winds burning and creeping things only to remove the danger from weather and for living in seclusion i mean that's that's the spiritual purpose of your of your dwelling uh the spiritual purpose of dwelling is to give you a place which is safe from the elements and marauding animals and things like that and quiet enough so that sometime in the day you can sit silently

217
00:21:44,096 --> 00:21:45,358
And that's it.

218
00:21:45,378 --> 00:21:50,247
That's the spiritual need for your house.

219
00:21:51,868 --> 00:21:54,173
And then the final one is wisely reflecting.

220
00:21:54,953 --> 00:22:04,890
I use the support for sick and medicinal requisites only to ward off painful feelings that have arisen and from the maximum freedom from disease.

221
00:22:06,355 --> 00:22:08,676
And it doesn't actually say it here.

222
00:22:08,696 --> 00:22:10,098
That's the actual verse we say.

223
00:22:10,159 --> 00:22:19,107
But what we're supposed to be content with is fermented cow's urine.

224
00:22:19,128 --> 00:22:20,329
Now, think on that.

225
00:22:20,349 --> 00:22:28,679
Supposing you went to the doctor with pneumonia and he said, listen, the only thing I can offer you is fermented cow's urine.

226
00:22:28,699 --> 00:22:29,740
I mean, would you say, what?

227
00:22:31,141 --> 00:22:34,724
Or would you say, well, should I take it in spoonfuls or should I...

228
00:22:36,577 --> 00:22:45,736
See, that's your basic line in the Ayurvedic medicine, you know, like fermented cows, you're right.

229
00:22:47,179 --> 00:22:51,346
So it's like that also gives us a certain, what should we say, a certain...

230
00:22:53,250 --> 00:22:54,833
a way of being with the NHS.

231
00:22:55,815 --> 00:22:59,378
People complain about the NHS, but they don't want to lose it.

232
00:22:59,420 --> 00:23:00,780
They're absolutely holding on to it.

233
00:23:00,942 --> 00:23:02,703
That's the National Health Service.

234
00:23:02,723 --> 00:23:04,987
They don't want to lose it by any means.

235
00:23:05,067 --> 00:23:06,028
It's their thing.

236
00:23:06,108 --> 00:23:11,896
Anybody, any politician who says they're going to do something about the NHS, everybody goes berserk.

237
00:23:12,057 --> 00:23:12,938
But everybody complains.

238
00:23:13,298 --> 00:23:13,980
It's not good enough.

239
00:23:14,019 --> 00:23:14,840
It's not quick enough.

240
00:23:14,881 --> 00:23:15,382
It's not this.

241
00:23:15,402 --> 00:23:15,882
It's not that.

242
00:23:16,663 --> 00:23:19,507
And what they need to do is contemplate fermented cows.

243
00:23:19,527 --> 00:23:20,067
You're right.

244
00:23:22,208 --> 00:23:23,710
And then they'd be very happy.

245
00:23:24,911 --> 00:23:29,256
They'd say, oh my goodness, you know, all these machines and medicines, amazing.

246
00:23:30,857 --> 00:23:35,523
So that's another way that we can look at our lives when we return, you see.

247
00:23:35,564 --> 00:23:37,246
It's just like, what do I need, you see?

248
00:23:37,425 --> 00:23:40,209
I remember these are the basic needs for the spiritual life.

249
00:23:40,609 --> 00:23:50,240
I remember in the order, the Buddha sort of made it so that monks were completely dependent upon lay people.

250
00:23:50,221 --> 00:23:53,223
I mean, you know, we can't touch money.

251
00:23:53,243 --> 00:23:54,244
We're not supposed to touch money.

252
00:23:54,325 --> 00:23:56,587
So people have to support us.

253
00:23:59,912 --> 00:24:01,373
We can't cook, you see.

254
00:24:02,193 --> 00:24:13,165
He made it very difficult to exit from society, even though he's always talking about seek seclusion, be on your own, get away from the madding crowd.

255
00:24:13,185 --> 00:24:15,208
He's always talking about that.

256
00:24:15,228 --> 00:24:19,553
But he wouldn't let you do this thing about, you know, getting your own little place out of the country and

257
00:24:21,102 --> 00:24:23,726
like Sadi Panyan and getting on with it by yourself.

258
00:24:24,307 --> 00:24:29,615
There always had to be this connection with lay people.

259
00:24:30,438 --> 00:24:38,570
So obviously in lay life, you need much more than just a place where you can sit and so on.

260
00:24:39,090 --> 00:24:46,103
But even so, you can take this as your absolute standard and then work up from that.

261
00:24:46,123 --> 00:24:48,306
You know, just keep asking, well, what do you actually need?

262
00:24:48,405 --> 00:24:49,407
What do you actually need?

263
00:24:49,729 --> 00:24:51,852
So there are social needs, too.

264
00:24:51,872 --> 00:24:54,056
I mean, if you're working, you can't turn up in rags.

265
00:24:54,455 --> 00:25:02,769
So there's certain behaviors that society would ask of us, which would come under the idea of refinement.

266
00:25:05,769 --> 00:25:19,083
So the next thing is to recognize this loop, this feedback loop that's in the eightfold path.

267
00:25:20,164 --> 00:25:29,054
So mainly in the ten of arteries, well, it's pretty well universal, but we start with wisdom.

268
00:25:29,094 --> 00:25:32,537
We start with trying to understand how we create suffering for ourselves.

269
00:25:33,817 --> 00:25:38,063
And what this does is it creates a change in our attitudes.

270
00:25:38,103 --> 00:25:43,330
That's why in our meditation we're always looking at the attitude which is driving the thought.

271
00:25:43,351 --> 00:25:45,493
The thoughts themselves are only expressions.

272
00:25:46,736 --> 00:25:56,009
So the wisdom is to realize that there are certain attitudes which are creating problems for us and certain attitudes which are creating happiness.

273
00:25:56,770 --> 00:26:00,836
And we'll define happiness at some point.

274
00:26:00,817 --> 00:26:08,367
So we talk about seeing these three characteristics, the impermanence of things.

275
00:26:08,728 --> 00:26:11,932
That undermines attachment when you see the impermanence of things.

276
00:26:12,353 --> 00:26:15,257
Why should you be so attached to this Ming vase?

277
00:26:15,538 --> 00:26:17,400
You should give it away.

278
00:26:17,420 --> 00:26:27,734
If you look at all your attachments, you can see that this is actually causing mental disturbance underneath.

279
00:26:28,930 --> 00:26:38,648
And then there's the whole problem of dukkha, which is seeing the mechanism, this desiring, this way that we relate to things.

280
00:26:38,669 --> 00:26:41,074
And again, it's to do with attachment.

281
00:26:41,094 --> 00:26:44,661
Attachment, remember, is a psychological dependency on something.

282
00:26:45,181 --> 00:26:48,086
for our happiness, which isn't under our control.

283
00:26:48,487 --> 00:26:56,501
Either because it isn't under our control, it disappears, or somebody takes it, or it just is impermanent.

284
00:26:56,521 --> 00:26:57,824
That's the end of that.

285
00:26:57,844 --> 00:27:06,480
And the anatta is recognizing that this whole relationship begins with this sense of me.

286
00:27:06,747 --> 00:27:09,390
And this me creates a little barrier.

287
00:27:09,690 --> 00:27:11,031
Well, sometimes a big barrier.

288
00:27:11,393 --> 00:27:13,414
There's me and you, you see.

289
00:27:14,056 --> 00:27:24,708
And by letting go of the sharpness of that barrier, by perceiving how that barrier manifests, then we begin to move towards the opposite.

290
00:27:24,949 --> 00:27:25,990
How does it manifest?

291
00:27:26,029 --> 00:27:27,971
Well, it manifests, first of all, in selfishness.

292
00:27:28,712 --> 00:27:29,673
That's your first manifest.

293
00:27:29,693 --> 00:27:34,559
Every time, you know, these sneaky little selfishnesses, you know, where you take just that...

294
00:27:35,147 --> 00:27:37,171
cake which is just a bit bigger than the others.

295
00:27:39,232 --> 00:27:41,536
Everybody gets a piece, you know.

296
00:27:42,096 --> 00:27:44,078
I'm here first.

297
00:27:45,441 --> 00:27:52,711
You can see the struggle I go through every time I have to say food.

298
00:27:52,730 --> 00:27:55,554
So, constantly letting go of the bigger piece of cake.

299
00:27:56,715 --> 00:27:59,298
It's a misery.

300
00:28:00,612 --> 00:28:09,023
So and then there's the business of acquisitiveness, selfishness.

301
00:28:09,243 --> 00:28:10,385
So we've done that selfishness.

302
00:28:10,405 --> 00:28:20,460
Then there's the business of these aversions, you know, petty little aversions, irritations, little bits of spite and all that sort of stuff.

303
00:28:20,930 --> 00:28:26,799
And then there's this cruelty business where we get our own back and poke people in the eye and stuff like that.

304
00:28:27,761 --> 00:28:34,394
And as we see that, this is actually, when we get into it as a bodily feeling, they're not pleasant at all.

305
00:28:35,174 --> 00:28:36,056
Not pleasant at all.

306
00:28:36,076 --> 00:28:42,667
And you think, well, you know, this feeling of selfishness is churning me up, this feeling

307
00:28:43,643 --> 00:28:49,453
Feelings of aversion, of burning, you know, cruelty, so cold within me, things like that.

308
00:28:49,954 --> 00:28:53,080
Being in the field, you feel the discomfort of them.

309
00:28:53,101 --> 00:28:56,006
And, of course, you want to move away from that.

310
00:28:56,287 --> 00:28:58,852
And the movement is towards the opposite, of course.

311
00:28:59,251 --> 00:29:05,904
Selfishness, towards generosity, hatred to love and cruelty towards compassion.

312
00:29:07,251 --> 00:29:16,799
And that movement is, as we've said during the week, it's a sublimation.

313
00:29:17,019 --> 00:29:18,101
I mean, I rather like that word.

314
00:29:18,602 --> 00:29:29,651
You know, I get it from chemistry, where some substances go from solid to liquid to air to gas, but some just go from solid to gas.

315
00:29:30,332 --> 00:29:32,294
And the word for that, I believe, is sublimating.

316
00:29:32,693 --> 00:29:37,258
So when we let go of a bit of hatred, it immediately sublimates.

317
00:29:37,238 --> 00:30:02,250
into its opposite love it's not as though there's an in-between bit where there's a sort of hate love thing it just pops into the other into the other category you see and it's there as potential and it manifests in our actions and if you take any any uh any attitude which is unwholesome it will move towards his opposite

318
00:30:02,737 --> 00:30:07,523
So the one I normally would centre on is loneliness.

319
00:30:07,544 --> 00:30:09,346
Loneliness is a big thing in our society.

320
00:30:10,107 --> 00:30:19,782
You know, the lack of extended families, elderly people, towards the positions which I'm moving myself, just stuck on their own.

321
00:30:20,371 --> 00:30:21,291
are getting lonely.

322
00:30:21,932 --> 00:30:25,298
So loneliness, of course, can lead to despair.

323
00:30:25,719 --> 00:30:29,464
It's a feeling of being unloved, unwanted, not feeling worthy.

324
00:30:29,505 --> 00:30:35,213
It's all that sort of rubbish that comes up inside us when we start feeling this loneliness.

325
00:30:36,415 --> 00:30:40,761
And of course, there's a need for most people to have communication.

326
00:30:41,482 --> 00:30:44,488
Just to talk to yourself in a mirror won't do.

327
00:30:45,733 --> 00:30:59,438
And when you actually sit in the midst of that awful feeling and you're just staying with it and staying with it, you see, it begins to lessen away and it's beginning to sublimate.

328
00:30:59,578 --> 00:31:01,442
So what does it move towards?

329
00:31:02,103 --> 00:31:07,573
Solitude.

330
00:31:08,869 --> 00:31:17,361
Solitude is being at peace with ourselves, just to be able to be completely happy on one's own.

331
00:31:18,926 --> 00:31:31,685
So if you take any of these negative states and just work out what its opposite are, you can purposefully move towards the opposite through certain exercises.

332
00:31:32,287 --> 00:31:38,655
And mainly the exercise is to stay with the unpleasant and wait for it to die away.

333
00:31:39,237 --> 00:31:44,444
You might not see the opposite immediately, but at least just to wait for it to fade or to begin to fade.

334
00:31:44,678 --> 00:31:49,143
And then one begins to see that there is an ending to this suffering.

335
00:31:49,163 --> 00:31:51,204
There's an ending to these mental states.

336
00:31:52,866 --> 00:31:56,551
And that all comes through our practice, through our practice of meditation.

337
00:31:56,571 --> 00:32:01,596
Now, this is where it then begins to translate itself into what we do.

338
00:32:02,097 --> 00:32:03,599
So, the right speech.

339
00:32:05,781 --> 00:32:10,887
It's not just, you know, stop telling great big whoppers and things like that.

340
00:32:12,454 --> 00:32:21,047
It's also to do with a refinement of speech, not wasting speech, not just talking for talking's sake.

341
00:32:21,807 --> 00:32:24,792
A refinement of speech, not using coarse language.

342
00:32:26,355 --> 00:32:41,195
Seeing the worthiness of really knowing what you're saying, of making it very deliberate.

343
00:32:44,685 --> 00:32:47,710
Not just rabbiting on about something.

344
00:32:49,952 --> 00:32:53,038
And then you get right action.

345
00:32:53,178 --> 00:33:01,430
So this is normally defined as just moving away from all those five training rules that we have.

346
00:33:01,509 --> 00:33:03,192
Not to kill, not to steal, etc.

347
00:33:03,471 --> 00:33:07,417
But remember, as soon as you move away from those, you're moving towards the opposite.

348
00:33:07,438 --> 00:33:11,963
So where now we've abandoned killing, we're now moving towards caring.

349
00:33:11,983 --> 00:33:12,464
Caring for

350
00:33:13,880 --> 00:33:21,993
Where we once might have not been so clever with our language, like exaggeration, you see.

351
00:33:22,013 --> 00:33:25,038
Exaggeration is a sort of soft lie, you might say.

352
00:33:25,058 --> 00:33:29,968
We're now being much more truthful, much more direct, much more simple.

353
00:33:30,909 --> 00:33:38,402
Where we once used coarse language, we now try to phrase our language with a little bit of beauty, you know, like reading poetry, things like that.

354
00:33:39,361 --> 00:33:44,366
And where there was useless speech, you know, you don't waste time on that.

355
00:33:44,967 --> 00:33:50,313
But don't get confused between useless speech and the ordinary pleasantries of daily life.

356
00:33:51,654 --> 00:33:57,961
In the monastic life where I was anyway, my monastery, which was a meditation monastery, nobody ever said good morning.

357
00:33:58,323 --> 00:34:01,385
I mean, you turned up with your bowl and you were silent.

358
00:34:01,720 --> 00:34:05,326
And then when you came out, nobody said, was that all right?

359
00:34:05,566 --> 00:34:05,987
That was it.

360
00:34:06,508 --> 00:34:08,690
It was in silence most of the time.

361
00:34:09,231 --> 00:34:13,177
So when I went to live with my mother, after my father died, I stayed with her for a while.

362
00:34:14,519 --> 00:34:19,789
One morning I came into the kitchen, you see, and began to say, when she turned around and said, well, good morning then.

363
00:34:21,371 --> 00:34:23,494
And I thought, right, okay.

364
00:34:23,914 --> 00:34:27,039
So from then on it was, how are you doing, mum?

365
00:34:27,059 --> 00:34:28,202
Come on, give her a hug.

366
00:34:28,581 --> 00:34:29,324
You know what I mean?

367
00:34:29,344 --> 00:34:29,583
It's like...

368
00:34:31,505 --> 00:34:35,045
And you forget these little pleasantries, which aren't useless speech.

369
00:34:35,065 --> 00:34:38,123
They're just ordinary, so we say, simple human communication.

370
00:34:39,688 --> 00:34:47,161
Sometimes you can make the mistake, I only made it once, where you think, well, you know, I've got to be sincere.

371
00:34:48,023 --> 00:34:49,925
When I speak, I must be sincere.

372
00:34:50,126 --> 00:35:00,422
So in the pleasantry of meeting people, say, and this happened to me when I was working at a college and a colleague was coming towards me and I was being sincere.

373
00:35:00,884 --> 00:35:03,367
So I said to him, how are you?

374
00:35:03,635 --> 00:35:09,123
And I said it in such a way that allowed him to spend 10 minutes telling me how he was.

375
00:35:11,646 --> 00:35:16,552
I was late for the class and I thought, no, just how are you all doing?

376
00:35:16,572 --> 00:35:17,293
How are you doing?

377
00:35:17,313 --> 00:35:17,835
I'm all right.

378
00:35:19,516 --> 00:35:27,268
So it's like you've got to temper what your ideas were, live and learn.

379
00:35:27,467 --> 00:35:29,731
And then there's right livelihood.

380
00:35:29,751 --> 00:35:32,916
And I think the key to right livelihood is the word service.

381
00:35:33,300 --> 00:35:38,135
When we see our work as service, then of course everything seems to work for us.

382
00:35:38,958 --> 00:35:45,960
So from a point of view of service, service demands a certain humility, by which I mean a reality about ourselves.

383
00:35:46,362 --> 00:36:03,018
So when I offer my services to the company or to the workplace or to somebody in therapy or whatever I'm doing, when I'm offering my services, right, I'm open to the fact that they might not meet with the situation.

384
00:36:03,958 --> 00:36:05,099
You know, they might not be good enough.

385
00:36:05,719 --> 00:36:07,541
They might not be the right ones, you see.

386
00:36:08,041 --> 00:36:11,885
But if it's come with the heart of service, that's not a problem.

387
00:36:12,867 --> 00:36:12,927
No.

388
00:36:14,577 --> 00:36:17,039
I remember once going for an interview.

389
00:36:17,539 --> 00:36:24,326
I didn't get the job and I was in the waiting room and I was in the sitting room waiting to go in for the interview.

390
00:36:25,226 --> 00:36:33,875
And at the end of the interview, I came out and I knew I'd botched it.

391
00:36:34,454 --> 00:36:42,862
And I came out and I sat there and the guy and this man next to me said, I wonder what they're looking for.

392
00:36:43,483 --> 00:36:45,806
See, we would say, I wonder who?

393
00:36:46,567 --> 00:36:47,288
He was very wise.

394
00:36:47,608 --> 00:36:49,230
It's not who they're looking for.

395
00:36:49,449 --> 00:36:53,454
It's what you can offer a firm or your employees looking for.

396
00:36:54,175 --> 00:36:56,237
And when you think, well, what are my skills?

397
00:36:56,257 --> 00:36:58,219
What are my aptitudes?

398
00:36:58,719 --> 00:36:59,621
That's what you're offering.

399
00:37:00,282 --> 00:37:04,005
But if you put yourself in there, then there's always going to be a real downer.

400
00:37:04,025 --> 00:37:05,246
You know, they don't want me.

401
00:37:05,887 --> 00:37:07,489
But it's not a matter of wanting you.

402
00:37:07,550 --> 00:37:08,911
They just want your skills.

403
00:37:08,931 --> 00:37:09,492
You see what I mean?

404
00:37:10,534 --> 00:37:13,358
And this also takes us into this whole area of ambition.

405
00:37:13,780 --> 00:37:18,365
So a lot of people, when they come into this sort of teaching, think, oh, that's ego-driven.

406
00:37:18,726 --> 00:37:20,489
I shouldn't be seeking power.

407
00:37:20,550 --> 00:37:21,471
I shouldn't be seeking that.

408
00:37:22,411 --> 00:37:31,125
But not if you're at service, because if you see your talents as being to the service of humankind, you have a duty to offer it.

409
00:37:31,105 --> 00:37:59,677
so if you see yourself as being able to do that job you know whatever the prime minister or whatever you should do it because that's your duty to offer that service and that takes that that allows you to uh to grow because the buddha talks about um right livelihood as a as a place where you grow so if you think about the effect of the work you've done in your lives on your personality on your character

410
00:38:01,429 --> 00:38:05,577
I mean, you can always tell somebody's been a policeman because they're always suspicious.

411
00:38:08,442 --> 00:38:10,666
And the teacher always asks questions they can answer.

412
00:38:11,648 --> 00:38:16,536
I mean, it's like it does affect you, you see.

413
00:38:16,556 --> 00:38:21,666
Somebody who's in the caring professions, they affect the way they relate to people.

414
00:38:23,771 --> 00:38:35,003
We shouldn't think so darkly about the armed forces as Buddhist, in the Buddhist, as a Buddhist or from a Buddhist point of view.

415
00:38:38,467 --> 00:38:46,836
I know of one place who would not allow, it's a Buddhist center, who would not allow soldiers or anybody to do with the armed forces to enter into the property.

416
00:38:47,697 --> 00:38:51,822
And I thought, well, you know, this is all a wrong understanding really.

417
00:38:52,121 --> 00:38:56,072
Now, you might say, well, these people are trained to kill, right?

418
00:38:56,092 --> 00:38:56,853
And they are, of course.

419
00:38:57,054 --> 00:38:59,018
That's what they say.

420
00:38:59,039 --> 00:39:00,342
Their job is to kill.

421
00:39:00,782 --> 00:39:03,309
But it's to kill in the line of duty.

422
00:39:03,590 --> 00:39:06,215
It's to kill in terms of protection.

